Reinventing Crew Scheduling for Enterprise & U.S. Expansion
Context
At Rentman, we identified two major strategic priorities:
Expand deeper into the U.S. market
Move upmarket into Enterprise accounts
While our Crew Scheduling product was strong, it was originally optimized for mid-market event companies. Enterprise and U.S. customers required:
Higher configurability
Stronger process control
Clearer workflow ownership
Improved planning speed
Better communication and confirmation loops
To support this shift, I led the creation and evangelization of a 2-year product vision for Crew Scheduling.
This was not about shipping isolated features.
It was about defining where the product needed to go strategically.

1. Empathize with the Problem
Before defining a future state, we went deep into understanding the current one.
1.1 Dogfooding (Use Our Own Product)
We scheduled real-life scenarios in Rentman internally:
Multi-day projects
Crew substitutions
Last-minute time changes
Freelance confirmations
Cross-project resource conflicts
Pain points we experienced:
Too many manual steps to plan crew
Limited overview for large-scale operations
Friction in confirming availability
Hard to distinguish draft vs definitive planning
Insufficient customization for enterprise workflows
We felt the friction ourselves.

1.2 Catfooding (Use Competitors’ Products)
We tested competitive tools in the U.S. and EU markets.
Observations:
Some tools were stronger in workflow structure
Others had better visibility into resource utilization
Few supported enterprise-level customization cleanly
Most lacked strong integration between planning and communication
This helped us understand both our strengths and blind spots.

1.3 Research & Data Insights
We gathered insights from:
Customer interviews
Sales feedback
Customer Success escalations
Productboard requests
Usage analytics
Enterprise deal losses
Patterns emerged:
U.S. customers required more structured confirmation workflows
Enterprise clients wanted process control & status visibility
Planning speed directly impacted operational profitability
Communication loops caused bottlenecks

1.4 Jobs to Be Done Analysis
Using the Jobs to Be Done framework, we reframed the problem.
Core Jobs Identified
Functional Jobs
“When planning a project, I want to assign the right crew member quickly, so that my project stays on schedule.”
“When managing multiple projects, I want a clear overview, so I can avoid staffing conflicts.”
“When sending confirmations, I want clarity, so I don’t chase people manually.”
Emotional Jobs
“I want to feel in control of complex planning.”
“I want confidence that I didn’t miss something.”
“I want to look professional towards clients and crew.”
Enterprise-Specific Jobs
“I need visibility into planning status across departments.”
“I need standardized workflows across teams.”
This analysis shaped our direction.

2. Create the Vision Type
Instead of jumping to features, we created a multi-layered product vision artifact.
2.1 Customer Journey Story (“Uber Type” Narrative)
We created a future-state story:
“Imagine planning crew as effortlessly as requesting an Uber.”
Select function
Instantly see best-fit crew
Click-to-plan
Auto-validate availability
Send confirmation
Track status live
Planning becomes proactive instead of reactive.

2.2 Mockups & Interface Evolution
We visualized:
Click-to-plan workflows
Improved color-coded scheduling states
Collapsible project views
360° overview dashboards
Availability hover previews
Confirmation request flows
Team-based crew lists
Many of these were later reflected in the improvements shared publicly:
Reference blog:
“Get ready for an even better Crew Scheduling product”
Key improvements included:
Click-to-plan (3x faster scheduling)
Improved planning overview with visual status differentiation
Filters for fully scheduled functions
Collapsible project views
Crew list grouping
Confirmation requests
Better screen space optimization

2.3 Future Press Release Exercise
We drafted a future press-style narrative:
“Rentman launches the most powerful crew planning experience for enterprise event teams.”
Positioning focused on:
Speed
Control
Enterprise-grade visibility
Workflow ownership
Reduced operational chaos
This helped align messaging early.

2.4 Whitepaper Vision
We documented:
Market shift toward complex, distributed event operations
U.S. expansion requirements
Enterprise standardization needs
Planning as a strategic differentiator
The product was no longer just a scheduling tool —
it became an operations backbone.

3. Validation
Before full rollout, we conducted:
Short validation sessions with selected enterprise customers
U.S.-focused feedback calls
Early mockup walkthroughs
Feedback loops with Customer Success
Validation insights:
Click-to-plan significantly reduced planning friction
Clear draft vs definitive distinction increased confidence
Overview customization was highly valued
Confirmation workflows reduced operational follow-up
This gave us confidence that the vision aligned with real-world needs.

4. Evangelize
A product vision only works if adopted internally.
4.1 Team
Presented vision walkthrough sessions
Shared future press release narrative
Created mockup demos
Linked roadmap items to strategic objectives
4.2 Stakeholders
Connected improvements to U.S. expansion goals
Demonstrated enterprise readiness
Framed it as competitive differentiation
4.3 Cross-Functional Teams
Enabled Sales with vision narrative
Equipped Marketing with forward-looking messaging
Supported Customer Success with clear positioning
4.4 Leadership
Aligned vision with:
U.S. revenue growth
Enterprise deal size increase
Long-term product differentiation

Outcomes
Within the following roadmap cycle:
Click-to-plan reduced scheduling time significantly
Improved overview increased planning accuracy
Enterprise conversations became stronger
Product narrative matured from feature-led to vision-led
The Crew Scheduling product evolved from:
“A functional planning tool”
to
“A scalable enterprise crew operations platform.”

Strategic Impact
This vision supported:
U.S. expansion strategy
Enterprise market entry
Stronger differentiation against point solutions
Long-term platform positioning
It ensured that every incremental improvement tied back to a coherent 1–2 year direction.

Reflection
This project demonstrated my ability to:
Move from insight gathering to long-term product vision
Use Jobs to Be Done to structure thinking
Align product strategy with company strategy
Validate vision before full investment
Evangelize across the organization
It was not just about improving scheduling.
It was about defining where Crew Planning needed to go to support Rentman’s next growth phase.


